      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Swipe Post / Slide Post</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>carousel post</strong> is an organic social media post made up of 2-20 slides that users swipe through horizontally. Available on Instagram, LinkedIn (as document posts), TikTok Photo Mode, and Facebook, carousels are the highest-performing organic format on Instagram — earning <strong>1.9x more reach</strong> and <strong>3x more engagement</strong> than single-image posts according to Socialinsider's 2024 data.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Slide range</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2-20 (Instagram)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Engagement lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3x vs single image</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Sweet spot</div>
            <div class="tms-value">7-10 slides</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The Instagram algorithm gives every carousel two shots at the same viewer. If someone scrolls past without engaging on slide 1, Instagram re-serves the post with slide 2 as the cover. That single mechanic is why carousels compound reach — and why organic strategies built on them outperform video-only or single-image feeds.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a carousel post?</h2>
        <p>A carousel post is a single organic post containing 2-20 (Instagram) or up to 300 (LinkedIn document posts) sequential slides. Users tap or swipe to move through the deck. The whole thing counts as one post, sharing one caption and one comment thread.</p>
        <p>Different platforms brand and shape the format differently:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Instagram carousel</strong> — 2-20 slides, images or videos, square or 4:5</li>
          <li><strong>LinkedIn document post</strong> — a PDF uploaded to LinkedIn that renders as a native swipeable carousel</li>
          <li><strong>TikTok Photo Mode</strong> — 2-35 image slides paired with a music track</li>
          <li><strong>Facebook carousel</strong> — 2-10 slides on Pages and profiles</li>
          <li><strong>Pinterest carousel Pin</strong> — 2-5 slides on a single Pin</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The two-slide algorithm boost</div>
          <p>Instagram's algorithm re-serves carousels to viewers who scrolled past on the first attempt, this time leading with a later slide as the cover. Meta's own research shows this doubles the effective reach ceiling of the format vs. single-image posts.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why carousel posts matter</h2>
        <p>Every organic feed is a fight for stopped scrolls. Carousels win five ways:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Two-shot algorithm boost.</strong> The re-serve mechanic on Instagram gives carousels a structural reach advantage.</li>
          <li><strong>3x engagement rate.</strong> Multi-slide swipes register as dwell time. Every extra slide viewed is a signal to the algorithm.</li>
          <li><strong>Save-worthy by design.</strong> Framework, list, and how-to carousels get saved at 2-4x the rate of single images because they're worth returning to.</li>
          <li><strong>Room for depth.</strong> A single image can carry one hook. Ten slides carry ten. That's why carousels dominate B2B thought leadership on LinkedIn.</li>
          <li><strong>No production cost.</strong> A designer can build a 10-slide carousel in the time it takes to shoot one Reel. The ROI on time is unmatched.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">The 3-part carousel post structure</h2>
        <p>Every high-performing carousel follows the same three-phase spine.</p>

        <h3>Slide 1 — the hook</h3>
        <p>The cover slide has one job: stop the scroll and earn the tap. It's a headline, not a visual. Proven cover patterns:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Contrarian claim</strong> — "You don't need more content. You need better distribution."</li>
          <li><strong>Numbered promise</strong> — "7 landing-page tests that lifted CVR 34% (with data)"</li>
          <li><strong>Curiosity gap</strong> — "The email that turned a $2K/mo client into $50K/mo"</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Big type. High contrast. Legible on a 3-inch screen. Anything else is decoration.</p>

        <h3>Slides 2-8 — the payoff</h3>
        <p>Each slide advances the sequence. One idea per slide, one visual per idea. Use consistent typography and brand palette so the deck reads as one piece.</p>
        <p>Add micro-hooks between slides — arrows, "here's why," visible tension — so the reader keeps swiping. If slide 4 could be dropped without losing meaning, drop it.</p>

        <h3>Final slide — the CTA</h3>
        <p>The last slide converts the read into an action:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><em>"Save this for your next launch."</em></li>
          <li><em>"Follow @handle for the full framework."</em></li>
          <li><em>"Full playbook in the link in bio."</em></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Carousel post specs by platform</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Platform</th><th>Slides</th><th>Aspect ratio</th><th>Best use case</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
