              <tr><td><strong>LinkedIn document post</strong></td><td>Up to 300 pages</td><td>Any (PDF)</td><td>B2B insights, playbooks, reports</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>TikTok Photo Mode</strong></td><td>2-35</td><td>9:16 or 1:1</td><td>Trend-driven storytelling, memes</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Facebook</strong></td><td>2-10</td><td>1:1</td><td>Product highlights, event recaps</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Pinterest carousel Pin</strong></td><td>2-5</td><td>1:1 or 2:3</td><td>Step-by-step tutorials, recipes</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real carousel post examples that worked</h2>

        <h3>1. B2B consultant grows LinkedIn from 200 to 2,000+ views</h3>
        <p>A fractional CMO switched from text-only posts to weekly 10-slide document posts breaking down GTM frameworks. Reach per post climbed from ~200 impressions to 2,000+ within six weeks. Two document posts crossed 100K impressions in the first quarter.</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Structure that consistently worked</span><br>
          Slide 1: <span class="uf-new">"5 GTM mistakes I see every week"</span><br>
          Slides 2-6: <span class="uf-new">One mistake per slide + fix</span><br>
          Slide 7: <span class="uf-new">Framework recap</span><br>
          Slide 8: <span class="uf-new">"DM me 'GTM' for the full audit template"</span>
        </div>

        <h3>2. Skincare DTC brand triples saves on Instagram</h3>
        <p>Instead of posting single product images, the brand tested 8-slide "before/after routine" carousels. Best-performing carousel: 5.2% save rate, 3.4% share rate. Save + share signals compounded — the post was pushed into Explore and reached 380K users organically.</p>

        <h3>3. Restaurant builds 15K local following</h3>
        <p>A local restaurant chain posted weekly 6-slide carousels — behind-the-scenes prep, staff highlights, menu launches. In 18 months the account grew from 500 to 15,000 followers, entirely organic, driven by the compounding engagement of the format.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Carousel post vs Reel vs single image — when to use each</h2>
        <p>All three organic formats have a job. Carousels sit between the depth of a long caption and the motion of a Reel.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use a carousel post when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You have a framework, list, or sequence to share</li>
              <li>The value takes 5+ points to convey</li>
              <li>You want saves + shares, not just likes</li>
              <li>Production bandwidth is limited (no video shoot)</li>
              <li>You're building an educational brand</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use a Reel or single image when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Motion or personality carries the message</li>
              <li>The idea is one sharp hook</li>
              <li>You want maximum discovery reach (Reels)</li>
              <li>Your audience skews video-native</li>
              <li>The topic doesn't warrant depth</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 carousel post best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Design slide 1 as a headline, not a visual.</strong> The cover is a text hook. Everything else is production value.</li>
          <li><strong>Aim for 7-10 slides.</strong> Socialinsider data shows this range maximizes both reach and engagement on Instagram and LinkedIn.</li>
          <li><strong>One idea per slide.</strong> Cluttered slides collapse the swipe rate.</li>
          <li><strong>Use consistent typography and palette.</strong> The carousel should read as one branded system, not eight design experiments.</li>
          <li><strong>Include micro-hooks between slides.</strong> "Here's why", numbered arrows, tension setups pull the swipe.</li>
          <li><strong>End with an explicit CTA.</strong> Save, follow, DM keyword, link in bio — pick one.</li>
          <li><strong>Repurpose across platforms with intent.</strong> A LinkedIn document post becomes an Instagram carousel with slides resized and copy rewritten. Never straight-copy — voice and length rules differ.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — carousels that never swipe</div>
          <p>If Instagram's insights show swipe-through rates below 40%, slide 1 isn't hooking — or slides 2-3 aren't paying it off. Check the visible tension between slides. If nothing pulls the reader forward, the carousel dies mid-deck and the engagement lift disappears.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common carousel post mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Front-loading slide 1 with the punchline</strong> — no reason to swipe if the answer is already there.</li>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent aspect ratios</strong> — mixing 1:1 and 4:5 slides breaks the swipe animation on Instagram.</li>
          <li><strong>Too many words per slide</strong> — mobile screens demand 15-30 words max per slide.</li>
          <li><strong>No CTA on the final slide</strong> — the swipe payoff is lost.</li>
          <li><strong>Text-only slides with no visual anchor</strong> — under-performs versus even simple illustrated slides.</li>
          <li><strong>Missing the caption</strong> — a strong carousel + weak caption still caps at like-level engagement. The caption drives the comment thread.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping LinkedIn document posts</strong> — they consistently outperform native LinkedIn image posts by 3-5x reach.</li>
        </ul>

